1. Examine the experimental groups within each grade. Do treatment groups have a similar distribution of pre-test scores? Explain why this question is important and why differences in pre-test scores can lead to incorrect inference about the effects of the intervention.

check <- summary (aov( treatment ~ pre_test, data = electric))
check
##              Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)
## pre_test      1   0.04 0.04221   0.167  0.683
## Residuals   190  47.96 0.25241

In the graph here, we illustrate the distribution of pretest scores, according to the grade and the treatment groups. We can see for each grade the pretest scores differs, and the median pre test score increases as the grade increases, by which we can infer that their overall performance is increasing as with the grade.

We see run an anova test to find if there is a relation between treatment groups and pre-test scores. We find from this test that there is no statistical difference between two treatment groups, for their pre-test scores. This test is extremely important as it tells us, before the intervention, the pre-test scores were similar, and the difference that we get in the post-test results, happens only because of the intervention, as everyone started at a similar level of pre-test scores. Or else we could not see the impact of treatment, and assess it properly.

2. What effect does the treatment have on the post test results? Present and interpret the regression results and provide a visualization displaying the effect of treatment.

reg2 <- lm(post_test ~ treatment, data = electric)
summary(reg2)

graph2 <- electric %>% ggplot (aes(x = as.factor(treatment), y = post_test,  fill = as.factor (treatment))) + geom_boxplot()  + labs (x = "Treatment", y = "Post-test scores", title = "Effect of Treatment on Post-test scores") 
graph2

The intercept here represents the test results a person would have gotten if there was no treatment present and there wasn’t any treatment effect. This means that a person would have gotten 94.321 in case there was no treatment and the marks will change by 5.657 in presence of a treatment, and no other variable. The p-value is 0.0269, which is significant and indicates that the effect of treatment has significance.

The box plot here indicates the spread of post test results for the conditions when treatment is present vs when treatment is not present. We can see that the median for the post test increased in the presence of a treatment.

graph3 <- electric %>%  ggplot (aes(x = pre_test, y = post_test , color = as.factor(treatment))) + geom_jitter() + geom_smooth(method = lm) + labs (x = "Pre-Test Scores", y = "Post-test Scores", title = "Effect of Pre-test scores on Post-Test scores") 
graph3
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

The intercept here represents the post test results without the presence of any pre-test happening, which is a kind of check. This means the score that a person would get would be 63.77507, if there is no pre-test happening.

The intercept for pre-test is 0.462, which means that the score for post-test would change by 0.462 if there is a pre-test in included.

The graph here presents the relation between the post test and pre-test in the presence of a treatment. The scores are higher when there is a treatment present, which shows the effect of the treatment. The coefficient here is seen to be significant, as the p value is less than 0.05, from which we can infer that the this coefficient has an effect on the post test.

We can also see from the graph that due to the treatment, the post test scores are higher for that group.

4. Does the effect of treatment depend on grade? Present and interpret the regression results and provide a visualization displaying the effect of treatment.

reg4 <- lm(effectoftreatment ~ grade + treatment + treatment*grade, data = electric)
summary (reg4)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = effectoftreatment ~ grade + treatment + treatment * 
##     grade, data = electric)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -19.081  -7.331  -2.312   6.038  37.253 
## 
## Coefficients:
##                 Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)       59.207      2.687  22.037   <2e-16 ***
## grade            -14.877      1.015 -14.661   <2e-16 ***
## treatment          9.206      3.800   2.423   0.0163 *  
## grade:treatment   -2.289      1.435  -1.595   0.1124

## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 10.52 on 188 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.7295, Adjusted R-squared:  0.7251 
## F-statistic:   169 on 3 and 188 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
graph4 <- electric %>%  ggplot (aes(x = as.factor(grade), y = effectoftreatment)) + geom_boxplot() + labs (x = "Grade", y = "Effect of Treatment", title = "Effect of treatment vs Grade") 
graph4

From this box-plot, we see that the effect of treatment decreases as the grade increases.

We might infer from this, that the treatment making much of a difference for the higher grade students. Intercept here is 59.207, which means that in the absence of effect of grade and treatment the score that a person would get is 59.207.

The coefficient for grade is -14.877, which means that in the absence of any other variables, and the presence of only grade, the change in the difference between post test and pre test would change by 14.877.

The coefficient for treatment is 9.206, which would mean that in the absence of any other variables and the presence of only treatment variable the effect on the difference between post test and pre test would change by 9.206.

The coefficient for interaction between treatment and grade, is not significant here, which means that there is no significant interaction between both of these variables. By this we could conclude that the effect of treatment does not depend on the grade.

5. Does the effect of treatment depend on the pretest results? Present and interpret the regression results and provide a visualization displaying the effect of treatment

graph5 <- electric %>% ggplot (aes (y = effectoftreatment, x = pre_test, fill = as.factor(treatment)) ) + geom_smooth (method =lm ) + geom_jitter () + labs (x = "Pre-Test Scores", y = "Effect of Treatment", title = "Effect of Treatment on Pre-test scores") 
graph5 
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

The intercept here is 58.89008, which tells us the the effect of treatment, which is the difference between post test and pre test, will be 58.89008, in the absence of the effect of treatment and any pre-test (pre-test result here might be 0, which means there is no pre-test?)

Coefficient of pre-test : the coefficient of pre-test is -0.5, which tells us, that in the presence of pre-test and no other variables, there would be a change of 0.5, on the difference between post test and pre test.

Coefficient for treatment : the coefficient for treatment is 10.15, which tells us that in the presence of only treatment, and no other variables, there would be a change of 10.15, on the difference between post test and pre test.

The interaction coefficient for treatment and pre-test is significant and is 0.075, which means that effect of treatment would cause 0.075 change of scores for the pre-test, and this change is significant.

The graph here shows the effect of treatment depending on the pre-test, for the groups which have treatment, vs which do not have treatment. It can be interpreted from the graph, that the effect of treatment decreases, as the pre-test scores increase.

2. Check (to the best of your ability) that none of the variables can be used to predict treatment.

regex2  <- lm (treatment ~ pre_test + grade, data = electric )
summary(regex2) 
##

## lm(formula = treatment ~ pre_test + grade, data = electric)

## Residuals:

## 
## Coefficients:
##              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  0.493008   0.091163   5.408 1.91e-07 ***
## pre_test     0.002042   0.002315   0.882    0.379    
## grade       -0.057884   0.074053  -0.782    0.435    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.5029 on 189 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.004099,   Adjusted R-squared:  -0.00644 
## F-statistic: 0.3889 on 2 and 189 DF,  p-value: 0.6783

#treatment should not depend on the grade, and pretest and hence our null hypothesis should be true, hence p values should not be significant Here we conduct a test to see the if the grade, and the pretest scores effect the treatment. Ideally we want to observe that there is no effect of these variables on the treatment, only then the treatment might be called effective. Hence our null hypothesis - that there is no effect of treatment on pre-test and grade has to be true. From this regression model, we see that the coefficients of pre-test and grade, have pvalues more than 0.05, suggesting that the null hypothesis is true, and there is no significant effect of these variables on the treatment
